uring the months preceding that tragic event. Was Ruth’s death an accident? Did she jump? Was she pushed? In an extended act of literary forensics, Goodall biographer Dale Peterson examines how Ruth’s death might have happened and explores some of the painful sequelae that haunted two of the survivors for the rest of their lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAccidentsxPsychological aspects. 0aBiological stationsxAccidentszTanzaniazGombe National Park. 0aChimpanzeeszTanzaniazGombe National Park. 0aGhostszTanzaniazGombe National Parky20th century. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszTanzaniazGombe National ParkxHistoryy20th century. 0aPrimatologistszTanzaniazGombe National Parky20th century. 0aPrimatologyzTanzaniazGombe National ParkxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096996440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969964423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520969964/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles